Nikola Tesla was a Serbian-American inventor, electrical engineer, mechanical engineer, and futurist best known for his contributions to the design of the modern alternating current (AC) electricity supply system. Born on July 10, 1856, in Smiljan, Croatia, Tesla"s pioneering work in the late 19th and early 20th centuries laid the foundation for many aspects of modern electrical engineering.

Tesla"s inventions include the induction motor, fluorescent lighting, and the development of high-voltage, high-frequency power experiments. His most notable achievement is the creation of the AC induction motor and the polyphase AC system, which revolutionized the field of electrical engineering and power distribution. The 'War of the Currents' between Tesla"s AC system and Thomas Edison"s direct current (DC) system ultimately led to the widespread adoption of AC power, which is the dominant power distribution system used today.

Tesla held over 300 patents worldwide and his ideas and innovations continue to influence modern technology, earning him a reputation as one of the most innovative scientists and engineers in history.
